04506nam a22005775i 9780814759417DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147594177 a10.18574/nyu/9780814784068.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547997  a(OCoLC)818819038  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF3890b.T54 2016 7aSOC0040002bisacsh04a345.7302770269223  aMS 64102rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123754:1 aTiger, Rebecca, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJudging Addicts :bDrug Courts and Coercion in the Justice System /cRebecca Tiger. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAlternative Criminology ;v600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Both Bad and Sick -- t2. Criminalizing Deviance -- t3. "The Right Thing to Do for the Right Reasons" -- t4. "Enlightened Coercion" -- t5. "Force Is the Best Medicine" -- t6. "Now That We Know the Medicine Works" -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe number of people incarcerated in the U.S. now exceeds 2.3 million, due in part to the increasing criminalization of drug use: over 25% of people incarcerated in jails and prisons are there for drug offenses. Judging Addicts examines this increased criminalization of drugs and the medicalization of addiction in the U.S. by focusing on drug courts, where defendants are sent to drug treatment instead of prison. Rebecca Tiger explores how advocates of these courts make their case for what they call "enlightened coercion," detailing how they use medical theories of addiction to justify increased criminal justice oversight of defendants who, through this process, are defined as both "sick" and "bad." Tiger shows how these courts fuse punitive and therapeutic approaches to drug use in the name of a "progressive" and "enlightened" approach to addiction. She critiques the medicalization of drug users, showing how the disease designation can complement, rather than contradict, punitive approaches, demonstrating that these courts are neither unprecedented nor unique, and that they contain great potential to expand punitive control over drug users. Tiger argues that the medicalization of addiction has done little to stem the punishment of drug users because of a key conceptual overlap in the medical and punitive approaches-that habitual drug use is a problem that needs to be fixed through sobriety. Judging Addicts presses policymakers to implement humane responses to persistent substance use that remove its control entirely from the criminal justice system and ultimately explores the nature of crime and punishment in the U.S. today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDrug abusexTreatmentxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aDrug addictsxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aDrug courtszUnited States. 0aDuress (Law)zUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814784068.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814759417zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814759417/original  a978-3-11-070644-4 New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA